.\" Manpage for aimap.
.\" Contact security@d5data.ai or open an issue on github.com/Nicholas-Kloster/aimap
.TH AIMAP 1 "April 2026" "aimap 1.3" "Security Tools"

.SH NAME
aimap \- AI infrastructure scanner: find exposed LLMs, vector databases, and ML services

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B aimap
.RB [ \-target
.IR IP | HOSTNAME | CIDR ]
.RB [ \-list
.IR FILE ]
.RB [ \-ports
.IR LIST ]
.RB [ \-threads
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-timeout
.IR DURATION ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR FILE ]
.RB [ \-v ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B aimap
is a purpose-built scanner for AI and machine learning infrastructure. Where
.BR nmap (1)
and
.BR nuclei (1)
identify that a service is running, aimap identifies
.I which AI/ML service
is running and whether it is exposing data, PII, credentials, or compute.
.PP
aimap is intended for defensive use: security teams running it against their own networks to discover shadow AI deployments, audit exposure before attackers do, and integrate AI-service checks into CI/CD deployment gates.
.PP
All probes are read-only HTTP GETs. aimap never writes, authenticates, or exploits. It is safe to run against production infrastructure you own.

.SH SCANNING PIPELINE
aimap operates in three phases:
.TP
.B Phase 1 \- Port discovery
Parallel TCP connect scan across the specified ports. Default port list covers AI-service defaults including Ollama, Qdrant, ChromaDB, Milvus, MLflow, Jupyter, Ray, and Docker Registry on common non-standard ports.
.TP
.B Phase 2 \- Service fingerprinting
For each open port, aimap matches against 36 built-in AI/ML service fingerprints using path and body signatures.
.TP
.B Phase 3 \- Deep enumeration
Service-specific enumerators inspect schemas, collections, models, experiments, and configuration to surface actionable findings (PII fields, unauthenticated RCE, credential exposure).

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-target " " \fIIP|HOSTNAME|CIDR\fR
Single target to scan. Accepts an IPv4 address, hostname, or CIDR block (e.g.,
.IR 10.0.0.0/24 ).
.TP
.BR \-list " " \fIFILE\fR
Path to a file containing targets, one per line. Lines starting with
.B #
are treated as comments and ignored.
.TP
.BR \-ports " " \fILIST\fR
Comma-separated list of ports to scan. Default:
.I 80,443,8080,8443,11434,8000,3000,6333,19530,9091,8888,8501,9090,5000,5001,4000,7860,3001,8265,51000,55000,2379,5678,9000,30000,18789
.TP
.BR \-threads " " \fIN\fR
Number of concurrent scan goroutines. Default:
.BR 20 .
Internal-network scans typically benefit from 50-100. External scans should stay at 10-20 to avoid tripping rate limits or alerting.
.TP
.BR \-timeout " " \fIDURATION\fR
Per-connection timeout. Default:
.BR 5s .
Reduce to 2-3s on low-latency internal networks; increase to 10s for external scans.
.TP
.BR \-o " " \fIFILE\fR
Write a full JSON report to
.IR FILE .
Machine-readable output suitable for CI/CD integration or diffing across scans.
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose output. Shows per-host match reasoning, which helps interpret unexpected findings.

.SH SUPPORTED SERVICES
aimap v1.3 fingerprints 36 AI/ML service types across seven categories:
.TP
.B Vector databases
Weaviate, ChromaDB, Qdrant, Milvus
.TP
.B LLM runtimes
Ollama, vLLM, SGLang, LocalAI, AI TTS Server, text-generation-webui
.TP
.B ML platforms
MLflow, TensorFlow Serving, Triton Inference Server, Ray Serve, Ray Dashboard, Kubeflow
.TP
.B Orchestration and UI
LangServe, Flowise, Dify, Open WebUI, SillyTavern, LiteLLM, BentoML
.TP
.B AI agent platforms
OpenHands, Mem0, Coolify, Clawdbot
.TP
.B Observability and infrastructure
Langfuse, Grafana, Prometheus, etcd, MinIO, n8n
.TP
.B Notebooks, dev, and adjacent
Jupyter Notebook, Open Directory, Docker Registry

.SH RISK LEVELS
aimap computes a risk level per service based on findings:
.TP
.B critical
Exploitable now, no authentication required. Examples: unauthenticated Jupyter code execution, exposed Flowise credentials endpoint, Dify with unclaimed admin account.
.TP
.B high
Sensitive data accessible without authentication. Examples: vector database with PII fields exposed, Langfuse trace data readable, MLflow experiments accessible.
.TP
.B medium
Information disclosure or misconfiguration. Examples: version leaks, CORS misconfiguration, service identified with empty data.
.TP
.B low
Service detected with minor issues. Examples: header disclosure.
.TP
.B info
Service identified, authentication in place, no actionable findings.
.PP
Escalation rule: if authentication status is
.B none
and any finding is
.BR high ,
the overall risk is promoted to
.BR critical .

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Scan a single internal host for AI services:
.B aimap \-target 10.1.2.3 \-v

.TP
Audit an entire internal /16 for shadow AI deployments:
.B aimap \-target 10.0.0.0/16 \-threads 100 \-timeout 3s \-o audit.json

.TP
Check a list of public-facing hosts for AI exposure:
.B aimap \-list public-ips.txt \-threads 10 \-timeout 10s \-o external.json \-v

.TP
CI/CD deployment gate (fail build on critical findings):
.B aimap \-target $DEPLOY_URL \-o check.json && jq '.enum_results[] | select(.risk_level == "critical")' check.json

.TP
Investigate a single suspected host with wide port coverage:
.B aimap \-target 10.5.5.5 \-v \-ports 8000,8080,8443,8888,9091,11434,6333,19530,5000,3000,7860,4000,51000,55000

.SH OUTPUT
aimap prints a color-coded terminal summary showing open ports, identified services, per-service findings, and an overall risk assessment.
.PP
With
.BR \-o ,
a complete JSON report is written containing:
.IP \(bu 2
Scan metadata (target, duration, ports scanned)
.IP \(bu 2
Open ports with banner data
.IP \(bu 2
Identified services with version and match details
.IP \(bu 2
Deep enumeration results per service
.IP \(bu 2
Findings with severity, category, and remediation-relevant context
.IP \(bu 2
Aggregate summary counts

.SH AUTHORIZATION
aimap performs active scanning (TCP connections and HTTP probes). Only run it against systems you own or have explicit written authorization to test. Unauthorized scanning of third-party infrastructure may violate local computer-misuse laws.
.PP
For passive reconnaissance of external targets, use dedicated OSINT tools instead (Shodan, Censys, Certificate Transparency logs).

.SH FILES
No configuration files. All options are controlled via command-line flags.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Scan completed successfully (findings may still be present; check output).
.TP
.B 1
Invalid arguments or failure opening target list file.

